SIMPLE: tripartite
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tripartite
<hw>Trip"ar*tite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>tripartitus</ets>; <ets>tri-</ets> (see <er>Tri-</er>) +
<ets>partitus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>partiri</ets> to part, to divide. See
<er>Part</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Divided into
three parts; triparted; <as>as, a <ex>tripartite</ex>
leaf</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having three corresponding parts or copies; <as>as,
to make indentures <ex>tripartite</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>A.
Smith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Made between three parties; <as>as, a
<ex>tripartite</ex> treaty</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tripartitely</ent>⟦br⟧
